There is limited movement of the right hip due to pain. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately reflects the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcapital fracture","Transcervical fracture","Intertrochanteric fracture","Basicervical fracture","Subtrochanteric fracture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a typical history and examination findings of a hip fracture. The X-ray shows a fracture line at the base of the femoral head, just below its widest part, which is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcapital fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. This is an intracapsular fracture of the femoral neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etranscervical fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the middle of the femoral neck, which is not the case here. The fracture line in this image is more proximal, closer to the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eintertrochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is an extracapsular fracture where the fracture line passes between the greater and lesser trochanters. This type of fracture is not seen in the provided image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasicervical fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at the base of the femoral neck, just proximal to the trochanters. The fracture in this image is more proximal than a basicervical fracture would be.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esubtrochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs below the lesser trochanter, within 5 cm of the lesser trochanter. The fracture in this image is clearly above the trochanters, ruling out this option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to accurately classify hip fractures as the type of fracture guides management. Intracapsular fractures like subcapital fractures are further classified using the Garden Classification, which considers the degree of displacement. This classification helps determine whether the fracture can be treated with internal fixation or requires arthroplasty. In this case, the fracture appears to be a Garden I or II (undisplaced or minimally displaced), which would typically be managed with internal fixation using cannulated screws.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An accurate assessment of the type of fracture of the neck of femur will help determine the treatment.","Subcapital fractures are intracapsular fractures where the fracture line is at the base of the femoral head.","The Garden Classification is used to grade intracapsular hip fractures and guides management decisions."],"references":["Callaghan JJ, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surgical Br. 2012;94:19-21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23118374/","Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017; 377:2053-62. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1611090"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1078"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1408"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1408"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8a4daae3-35cc-4275-8f7e-eddfb1b4d252.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8a4daae3-35cc-4275-8f7e-eddfb1b4d252.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":658}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T14:10:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T06:01:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1078"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52142"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34